âœ… Inheritance vs. Composition â€” Why Composition is Preferred
ğŸ”· 1. Inheritance (IS-A relationship)
A child class inherits properties and behaviors from a parent class.

Example:


class Dog extends Animal {}
ğŸ”· 2. Composition (HAS-A relationship)
A class contains an instance of another class and uses it to achieve functionality.

Example:


class Engine {}
class Car {
    Engine engine = new Engine(); // Composition
}
ğŸ” Why composition is often better than inheritance:
| Reason                              | Inheritance                                | Composition                            |
| ----------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------ | -------------------------------------- |
| ğŸ”’ **Tight coupling**               | Yes â€” child is tightly bound to parent     | No â€” more flexible and loosely coupled |
| ğŸ” **Flexibility**                  | Difficult to change parent-child structure | You can easily swap out components     |
| ğŸ§ª **Testing**                      | Harder to test in isolation                | Easier to mock and test                |
| ğŸ”„ **Runtime Behavior**             | Fixed at compile time                      | Can change behavior at runtime         |
| ğŸ§¬ **Reusability**                  | Inherits everything (even if not needed)   | Uses only what it needs                |
| âš ï¸ **Fragile Base Class Problem**   | Changes in parent can break child          | Less risk, as components are separate  |
| ğŸ”„ **Multiple Inheritance Support** | Not allowed in Java (classes)              | Easily done with multiple fields       |

ğŸ”§ Real-life Example:
ğŸ”¹ Inheritance:

class Printer {
    void print() { ... }
}
class SmartPrinter extends Printer {
    void scan() { ... }
}
Problem: SmartPrinter is forced to inherit everything from Printer, even things it doesn't need.

ğŸ”¹ Composition:

class Printer {
    void print() { ... }
}
class Scanner {
    void scan() { ... }
}
class SmartPrinter {
    Printer printer = new Printer();
    Scanner scanner = new Scanner();
}
âœ… Now SmartPrinter has only what it needs, and you can easily replace components if needed.

âœ… Summary (Interview Answer):
"While inheritance promotes code reuse, it leads to tight coupling and fragile designs. Composition offers greater flexibility, better encapsulation,
and easier testing by allowing classes to use only what they need. Thatâ€™s why modern design principles like SOLID favor composition over inheritance."